{"title_page": "Ninja Gaiden (arcade game)", "text_new": "{{More citations needed|date=June 2016}}\n{{Infobox video game\n|title=Ninja Gaiden\n|image=Ninja Gaiden arcade flyer.png\n|caption=Sales flyer for the arcade game.\n|developer=[[Tecmo]]\n|publisher={{vgrelease|[[Japan|JP]]/[[North America|NA]]/[[PAL]]|[[Tecmo]]}}{{vgrelease|NA|[[Atari Games]]}}{{vgrelease|NA|[[Hi-Tech Expressions]]}}{{vgrelease|EU|[[Ocean Software]]}}\n|director = H. Iijima\n|writer = H. Iijima\n|artist = Shinobu Iwabayashi\n|composer=Mikio Saitou<br>Ichiro Nakagawa<br>Ryuichi Nitta<br>Tamotsu Ebisawa\n|released={{collapsible list|title=October 1988|\n'''Arcade'''{{vgrelease|NA|October 17, 1988|EU|1988}}{{vgrelease|JP|February 1989}}\n'''DOS'''{{vgrelease|NA|1990}}{{vgrelease|NA|February 15, 1991 <small>(re-release)</small>}}\n'''Commodore 64'''{{vgrelease|NA|1990|EU|1990}}\n'''Amiga'''{{vgrelease|EU|1990}}\n'''Amstrad CPC'''{{vgrelease|EU|1990}}\n'''Atari ST'''{{vgrelease|EU|1990}}\n'''ZX Spectrum'''{{vgrelease|EU|1990}}\n'''Atari Lynx'''{{vgrelease|NA|1991}}\n'''IBM PC'''{{vgrelease|NA|19??}}\n'''Wii Virtual Console'''{{vgrelease|JP|July 28, 2009|PAL|November 13, 2009}}{{vgrelease|NA|December 21, 2009<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nintendo.com/whatsnew/detail/rpQF_Q37xeLw8On2hEAtGy8gmJwnNYqd |title=500th Downloadable Wii Game Makes for a Smashing Holiday Season |date=21 December 2009 |publisher=Nintendo of America |accessdate=22 December 2009}}</ref>}}}}\n|series=''[[Ninja Gaiden]]''\n|genre=[[Beat 'em up]]\n|modes=[[Two-player]], [[Cooperative gameplay|co-op]]\n|platforms={{collapsible list|title=Arcade|[[Commodore Amiga|Amiga]], [[Amstrad CPC]], [[Atari ST]], [[Atari Lynx]], [[Commodore 64]], [[DOS]], [[IBM PC]], [[Xbox (console)|Xbox]], [[Wii Virtual Console]], [[ZX Spectrum]]}}\n}}\n\n'''''Ninja Gaiden''''',{{efn|Later released in Japan as {{nihongo|'''''Ninja Ry\u016bkenden'''''|\u5fcd\u8005\u9f8d\u5263\u4f1d||lit. ''Ninja Dragon Sword Legend''}}}} later released in [[Europe]] as '''''Shadow Warriors''''', is a 1988 side-scrolling [[beat-'em-up]] originally released by [[Tecmo]] as a [[arcade game|coin-operated arcade video game]].<ref>{{cite web\n |url        =http://www.arcade-museum.com/game_detail.php?game_id=8881\n |title      =Ninja Gaiden\n |publisher  =The International Arcade Museum\n |accessdate =6 Oct 2013\n}}</ref>  It was first released in [[North America]], and [[Europe]] in [[1988 in video gaming|1988]] and in [[Japan]] in [[1989 in video gaming|1989]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Ninja Gaiden (Release Data)|url=http://www.gamefaqs.com/arcade/568362-ninja-gaiden/data|publisher=[[GameFAQs]]|accessdate=30 December 2011}}</ref> The ''Ninja Gaiden'' arcade game was produced and released almost simultaneously with its [[Ninja Gaiden (Nintendo Entertainment System)|home console counterpart]] for the [[Nintendo Entertainment System]], although they are different games with only a few similarities.<ref name=masatokato>{{cite web|url=http://www.hardcoregaming101.net/ninjagaiden/ninjagaiden12.htm|title=Ninja Gaiden at Hardcore Gaming 101 - Interview with Masato \"RUNMAL\" Kato|author=Hardcore Gaming 101 editorial staff|quote=Kato: Both (the arcade and NES versions of Ninja Gaiden) were developed side by side on the same floor, at the same time. However, we only shared the same title, while each team developed their game as they pleased.}}</ref> The designer of the arcade game is only credited as \"Strong Shima\", but Masato Kato, who worked on the NES version, identified him as one \"Mr. Iijima\".<ref name=\"RG92\">{{cite magazine |title=Signature Series: ''Ninja Gaiden'' |magazine=[[Retro Gamer]] |issue=92 |date=July 2011 |pages=78\u201381 |publisher=[[Imagine Publishing]] |location=[[Bournemouth]] |issn=1742-3155 |oclc=489477015}}</ref>\n\nHome versions of the ''Ninja Gaiden'' arcade game were released in [[Europe]] under the ''Shadow Warriors'' title in [[1990 in video gaming|1990]] by [[Ocean Software]] for five different computer platforms ([[Amiga]], [[Atari ST]], [[Commodore 64]], [[ZX Spectrum]], and [[Amstrad CPC]]) and in North America for [[IBM PC]] by [[Hi-Tech Expressions]]. An [[Atari Lynx]] version was also released. The arcade version of ''Ninja Gaiden'' is also included as a hidden bonus game in ''[[Ninja Gaiden Black]]'' for the [[Xbox (console)|Xbox]] in [[2005 in video gaming|2005]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://xbox.gamedaily.com/game/news/?gameid=531&id=5418 | title = Ninja Gaiden Extras Confirmed...Again | author = Brightman, James | publisher = GameDaily | date = February 10, 2004 | accessdate = 2006-08-23 }}{{dead link|date=September 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> The arcade game was published as a [[Virtual Console]] game for the [[Nintendo Wii]] in 2009, along with the Nintendo Switch on May 5th, and later May 9th on PS4 of 2019 by [[Hamster Corporation]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.hamster.co.jp/american_hamster/arcadearchives/switch/ninja_gaiden.htm|title=Arcade Archives {{!}} HAMSTER Corporation|website=www.hamster.co.jp|access-date=2019-05-14}}</ref><ref>https://store.playstation.com/en-us/product/UP0571-CUSA15609_00-HAMPRDC000000001?emcid=se-pi-194278</ref>\n\n==Gameplay==\n[[Image:Ninja Gaiden (arcade) gameplay.png|left|250px|thumb|The game's first stage, with the advertising sign having been damaged]]\nThe arcade version of ''Ninja Gaiden'' is a side-scrolling [[beat-'em-up]] where the player controls a ninja hired{{citation needed|date=March 2017}} to defeat an evil cult led by Bladedamus, a descendant of [[Nostradamus]] who seeks to fulfill his [[end time|end of the world]] prophecies and flooded the streets of the United States with criminals.<ref name=gamestno29>{{cite journal|journal=Gamest|script-title=ja:\u7d39\u4ecb - \u5fcd\u8005\u9f8d\u5263\u4f1d|author=Joe Yamada|language=Japanese|page=103|volume=29|date=February 1989|url=http://www.geocities.jp/arcadon765/Ryukenden.html|access-date=2010-01-03|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120704144734/http://www.geocities.jp/arcadon765/Ryukenden.html|archive-date=2012-07-04|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=famimaga198901>{{cite magazine|magazine=Family Computer Magazine|script-title=ja:\u307c\u304f\u305f\u3061\u30b2\u30fc\u30bb\u30f3\u91ce\u90ce|language=Japanese|author=[[Satoshi Tajiri]]|url=https://twitter.com/chou_nosuke/status/606052702246666241|date=1989-01-06|pages=114\u2013115|accessdate=2015-11-27}}</ref> The first player controls a ninja dressed in blue, while the second player controls one dressed in orange. Like most beat-'em-ups, the player proceed through stages by defeating enemies scattered through each area.\n\nThe controls consist of an eight-way joystick with a button installed on top and two additional action buttons for attacking and jumping. The button on top of the joystick allows the player character to grab onto any overhead bar or tightrope and hang from there. There are five primary techniques performed by pressing the joystick and buttons individually or in combination with each other. These consists of the \"Triple Blow Combination\" (a series of punches and kicks that serve as the player's standard attack), the \"Flying Neck Throw\" (performed by attacking the enemy while jumping),  the \"Hang Kick\" (performed by attacking the enemy while hanging from a bar), the \"Tightrope Walk\" (in which the player moves while hanging from or standing above a tightrope), and the \"Phoenix Backflip\" (a backflip performed after running into a wall), which becomes an attack if the player has a sword.\n\nThe player can destroy certain objects in the environment (such as telephone booths, signposts, dumpsters) by knocking or throwing enemies onto them. These will uncover hidden items that will award the player with bonus points, health recovery, time extensions and even an extra life. One particular item will temporarily arm the player with a sword that can be used up to ten times before reverting to his standard punches and kicks.\n\nThe game is mostly remembered for its morbid continue screen, where the player character is chained to a table, violently thrashing his head while a circular saw descends towards his body. If the player does not continue within the 10-second countdown, the screen fades to red(as if sprayed with blood), the ninja cries out in agony, and the words \"GAME OVER\" appears followed by dramatic music. ''[[Final Fight (video game)|Final Fight]]'', released a year later, had a similar sequence, with the characters tied up next to a stick of dynamite.\n\nThe first five stages are based on actual American cities and landmarks such as [[Los Angeles]], [[Brooklyn]], [[Las Vegas Valley|Las Vegas]], [[North Carolina]],{{citation needed|date=June 2016}} the [[Grand Canyon]], and a [[transcontinental railroad]]. The sixth and final stage is set inside the enemy's hideout. The recurring bosses include a [[sumo wrestler]], a pair of wrestlers resembling the [[tag team]] [[The Road Warriors]], and a trio of claw-wielding masked acrobats. The final boss, Bladedamus, wields two swords and has a fire breath attack.\n\n==Critical reaction==\n{{Video game reviews\n| YSinclair = 90%<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ysrnry.co.uk/articles/shadowwarriors.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2016-07-31 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160215225706/http://www.ysrnry.co.uk/articles/shadowwarriors.htm |archivedate=2016-02-15 }}</ref>\n| CRASH = 74%<ref>{{cite web|url=https://wos.meulie.net/pub/sinclair/magazines/Crash/Issue80/Pages/Crash8000048.jpg |format=JPG |title=Photographic image of game review |website=Wos.meulie.net |accessdate=2016-10-19}}</ref>\n| SUser = 75%<ref>{{cite web|url=https://wos.meulie.net/pub/sinclair/magazines/SinclairUser/Issue103/Pages/SinclairUser10300023.jpg |format=JPG |title=Photographic image of game review |website=Wos.meulie.net |accessdate=2016-10-19}}</ref>\n| CVG = 93%<ref>{{cite web|url=https://wos.meulie.net/pub/sinclair/magazines/Computer-and-Video-Games/Issue103/Pages/CVG10300017.jpg |format=JPG |title=Photographic image of game review |website=Wos.meulie.net |accessdate=2016-10-19}}</ref>\n| rev1 = ''[[Zzap!64]]''\n| rev1Score = 57%<ref>http://www.zzap64.co.uk/cgi-bin/displaypage.pl?issue=065&amp;page=079&amp;thumbstart=0&amp;magazine=zzap&amp;check=1</ref>\n}}\nThe game was well received. ''Your Sinclair'' praised the colorful graphics and interactive backgrounds. ''Crash'' liked the animation, but had grown tired of the genre. ''Sinclair User'' summed it up with \"There isn't really a speck of originality about Shadow Warriors. Nonetheless, it will be a stiff challenge.\" ''C+VG'' highlighted the music and sound effects.\n\n==Version differences==\n===Regional differences===\n''Ninja Ryukenden'', the [[Japan]]ese version, being the later version of the game, has the following differences from the other versions:\n* The ''Ninja Ryukenden'' version has a copyright date of 1989 instead of 1988, as befitting its later release. The Famicom version of ''Ninja Ryukenden'' was already released when the arcade game was distributed in Japan.<ref name=famimaga198901 />\n* The background music for Stage 4 was replaced by another tune that resembles in some parts [[Bach]]'s [[Toccata and Fugue in D Minor]]. And though the other background music tunes are the same as in the U.S. version, there are some minor additions to the tunes in the Japanese version.\n* The enemy characters cause normal damage during the final stage (a three-hit combo takes one square of player's life bar), unlike the U.S. version, where at the last stage, the standard enemies and the mid-bosses just need to hit the player once to take off one or two life squares, and the last boss can kill the player's character with just one attack.\n* A digitized voice shouts the game's title on the \"stage clear\" screen.\n\n===Virtual Console And Hamster Corp. Versions===\nThis game has been ported to the Nintendo Wii as a downloadable Virtual Console Arcade game. However, this contains the same changes found in ''Ninja Gaiden Black''.\n*The boss music in Stages 2 and 5 has been omitted from this version (due to the supposed similarity to [[Black Sabbath|Black Sabbath's]] \"[[Iron Man (song)|Iron Man]]\"); in turn, the regular background music keeps playing even after the bosses appear (which would normally prompt the quick music switch).\n*The use of the [[Star of David]] in the game's imagery (such as the rug at the end of Stage 4) was edited out.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Ninja Gaiden|''Ninja Gaiden'' series]]\n*''[[Rygar]]'', another Tecmo game referenced in background graffiti.\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Ninja Gaiden series}}\n{{Atari Lynx games}}\n\n[[Category:1988 video games]]\n[[Category:Amiga games]]\n[[Category:Amstrad CPC games]]\n[[Category:Arcade games]]\n[[Category:Atari Lynx games]]\n[[Category:Commodore 64 games]]\n[[Category:Cooperative video games]]\n[[Category:DOS games]]\n[[Category:Ninja Gaiden games]]\n[[Category:Ocean Software games]]\n[[Category:Side-scrolling beat 'em ups]]\n[[Category:Tecmo games]]\n[[Category:Virtual Console games]]\n[[Category:ZX Spectrum games]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in Japan]]\n[[Category:Video games set in Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Video games set in New York City]]\n[[Category:Brooklyn in fiction]]\n[[Category:Video games set in Arizona]]\n", "text_old": "{{More citations needed|date=June 2016}}\n{{Infobox video game\n|title=Ninja Gaiden\n|image=Ninja Gaiden arcade flyer.png\n|caption=Sales flyer for the arcade game.\n|developer=[[Tecmo]]\n|publisher={{vgrelease|[[Japan|JP]]/[[North America|NA]]/[[PAL]]|[[Tecmo]]}}{{vgrelease|NA|[[Atari Games]]}}{{vgrelease|NA|[[Hi-Tech Expressions]]}}{{vgrelease|EU|[[Ocean Software]]}}\n|director = H. Iijima\n|writer = H. Iijima\n|artist = Shinobu Iwabayashi\n|composer=Mikio Saitou<br>Ichiro Nakagawa<br>Ryuichi Nitta<br>Tamotsu Ebisawa\n|released={{collapsible list|title=October 1988|\n'''Arcade'''{{vgrelease|NA|October 1988|EU|1988}}{{vgrelease|JP|February 1989}}\n'''DOS'''{{vgrelease|NA|1990}}{{vgrelease|NA|February 15, 1991 <small>(re-release)</small>}}\n'''Commodore 64'''{{vgrelease|NA|1990|EU|1990}}\n'''Amiga'''{{vgrelease|EU|1990}}\n'''Amstrad CPC'''{{vgrelease|EU|1990}}\n'''Atari ST'''{{vgrelease|EU|1990}}\n'''ZX Spectrum'''{{vgrelease|EU|1990}}\n'''Atari Lynx'''{{vgrelease|NA|1991}}\n'''IBM PC'''{{vgrelease|NA|19??}}\n'''Wii Virtual Console'''{{vgrelease|JP|July 28, 2009|PAL|November 13, 2009}}{{vgrelease|NA|December 21, 2009<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nintendo.com/whatsnew/detail/rpQF_Q37xeLw8On2hEAtGy8gmJwnNYqd |title=500th Downloadable Wii Game Makes for a Smashing Holiday Season |date=21 December 2009 |publisher=Nintendo of America |accessdate=22 December 2009}}</ref>}}}}\n|series=''[[Ninja Gaiden]]''\n|genre=[[Beat 'em up]]\n|modes=[[Two-player]], [[Cooperative gameplay|co-op]]\n|platforms={{collapsible list|title=Arcade|[[Commodore Amiga|Amiga]], [[Amstrad CPC]], [[Atari ST]], [[Atari Lynx]], [[Commodore 64]], [[DOS]], [[IBM PC]], [[Xbox (console)|Xbox]], [[Wii Virtual Console]], [[ZX Spectrum]]}}\n}}\n\n'''''Ninja Gaiden''''',{{efn|Later released in Japan as {{nihongo|'''''Ninja Ry\u016bkenden'''''|\u5fcd\u8005\u9f8d\u5263\u4f1d||lit. ''Ninja Dragon Sword Legend''}}}} later released in [[Europe]] as '''''Shadow Warriors''''', is a 1988 side-scrolling [[beat-'em-up]] originally released by [[Tecmo]] as a [[arcade game|coin-operated arcade video game]].<ref>{{cite web\n |url        =http://www.arcade-museum.com/game_detail.php?game_id=8881\n |title      =Ninja Gaiden\n |publisher  =The International Arcade Museum\n |accessdate =6 Oct 2013\n}}</ref>  It was first released in [[North America]], and [[Europe]] in [[1988 in video gaming|1988]] and in [[Japan]] in [[1989 in video gaming|1989]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Ninja Gaiden (Release Data)|url=http://www.gamefaqs.com/arcade/568362-ninja-gaiden/data|publisher=[[GameFAQs]]|accessdate=30 December 2011}}</ref> The ''Ninja Gaiden'' arcade game was produced and released almost simultaneously with its [[Ninja Gaiden (Nintendo Entertainment System)|home console counterpart]] for the [[Nintendo Entertainment System]], although they are different games with only a few similarities.<ref name=masatokato>{{cite web|url=http://www.hardcoregaming101.net/ninjagaiden/ninjagaiden12.htm|title=Ninja Gaiden at Hardcore Gaming 101 - Interview with Masato \"RUNMAL\" Kato|author=Hardcore Gaming 101 editorial staff|quote=Kato: Both (the arcade and NES versions of Ninja Gaiden) were developed side by side on the same floor, at the same time. However, we only shared the same title, while each team developed their game as they pleased.}}</ref> The designer of the arcade game is only credited as \"Strong Shima\", but Masato Kato, who worked on the NES version, identified him as one \"Mr. Iijima\".<ref name=\"RG92\">{{cite magazine |title=Signature Series: ''Ninja Gaiden'' |magazine=[[Retro Gamer]] |issue=92 |date=July 2011 |pages=78\u201381 |publisher=[[Imagine Publishing]] |location=[[Bournemouth]] |issn=1742-3155 |oclc=489477015}}</ref>\n\nHome versions of the ''Ninja Gaiden'' arcade game were released in [[Europe]] under the ''Shadow Warriors'' title in [[1990 in video gaming|1990]] by [[Ocean Software]] for five different computer platforms ([[Amiga]], [[Atari ST]], [[Commodore 64]], [[ZX Spectrum]], and [[Amstrad CPC]]) and in North America for [[IBM PC]] by [[Hi-Tech Expressions]]. An [[Atari Lynx]] version was also released. The arcade version of ''Ninja Gaiden'' is also included as a hidden bonus game in ''[[Ninja Gaiden Black]]'' for the [[Xbox (console)|Xbox]] in [[2005 in video gaming|2005]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://xbox.gamedaily.com/game/news/?gameid=531&id=5418 | title = Ninja Gaiden Extras Confirmed...Again | author = Brightman, James | publisher = GameDaily | date = February 10, 2004 | accessdate = 2006-08-23 }}{{dead link|date=September 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> The arcade game was published as a [[Virtual Console]] game for the [[Nintendo Wii]] in 2009, along with the Nintendo Switch on May 5th, and later May 9th on PS4 of 2019 by [[Hamster Corporation]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.hamster.co.jp/american_hamster/arcadearchives/switch/ninja_gaiden.htm|title=Arcade Archives {{!}} HAMSTER Corporation|website=www.hamster.co.jp|access-date=2019-05-14}}</ref><ref>https://store.playstation.com/en-us/product/UP0571-CUSA15609_00-HAMPRDC000000001?emcid=se-pi-194278</ref>\n\n==Gameplay==\n[[Image:Ninja Gaiden (arcade) gameplay.png|left|250px|thumb|The game's first stage, with the advertising sign having been damaged]]\nThe arcade version of ''Ninja Gaiden'' is a side-scrolling [[beat-'em-up]] where the player controls a ninja hired{{citation needed|date=March 2017}} to defeat an evil cult led by Bladedamus, a descendant of [[Nostradamus]] who seeks to fulfill his [[end time|end of the world]] prophecies and flooded the streets of the United States with criminals.<ref name=gamestno29>{{cite journal|journal=Gamest|script-title=ja:\u7d39\u4ecb - \u5fcd\u8005\u9f8d\u5263\u4f1d|author=Joe Yamada|language=Japanese|page=103|volume=29|date=February 1989|url=http://www.geocities.jp/arcadon765/Ryukenden.html|access-date=2010-01-03|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120704144734/http://www.geocities.jp/arcadon765/Ryukenden.html|archive-date=2012-07-04|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=famimaga198901>{{cite magazine|magazine=Family Computer Magazine|script-title=ja:\u307c\u304f\u305f\u3061\u30b2\u30fc\u30bb\u30f3\u91ce\u90ce|language=Japanese|author=[[Satoshi Tajiri]]|url=https://twitter.com/chou_nosuke/status/606052702246666241|date=1989-01-06|pages=114\u2013115|accessdate=2015-11-27}}</ref> The first player controls a ninja dressed in blue, while the second player controls one dressed in orange. Like most beat-'em-ups, the player proceed through stages by defeating enemies scattered through each area.\n\nThe controls consist of an eight-way joystick with a button installed on top and two additional action buttons for attacking and jumping. The button on top of the joystick allows the player character to grab onto any overhead bar or tightrope and hang from there. There are five primary techniques performed by pressing the joystick and buttons individually or in combination with each other. These consists of the \"Triple Blow Combination\" (a series of punches and kicks that serve as the player's standard attack), the \"Flying Neck Throw\" (performed by attacking the enemy while jumping),  the \"Hang Kick\" (performed by attacking the enemy while hanging from a bar), the \"Tightrope Walk\" (in which the player moves while hanging from or standing above a tightrope), and the \"Phoenix Backflip\" (a backflip performed after running into a wall), which becomes an attack if the player has a sword.\n\nThe player can destroy certain objects in the environment (such as telephone booths, signposts, dumpsters) by knocking or throwing enemies onto them. These will uncover hidden items that will award the player with bonus points, health recovery, time extensions and even an extra life. One particular item will temporarily arm the player with a sword that can be used up to ten times before reverting to his standard punches and kicks.\n\nThe game is mostly remembered for its morbid continue screen, where the player character is chained to a table, violently thrashing his head while a circular saw descends towards his body. If the player does not continue within the 10-second countdown, the screen fades to red(as if sprayed with blood), the ninja cries out in agony, and the words \"GAME OVER\" appears followed by dramatic music. ''[[Final Fight (video game)|Final Fight]]'', released a year later, had a similar sequence, with the characters tied up next to a stick of dynamite.\n\nThe first five stages are based on actual American cities and landmarks such as [[Los Angeles]], [[Brooklyn]], [[Las Vegas Valley|Las Vegas]], [[North Carolina]],{{citation needed|date=June 2016}} the [[Grand Canyon]], and a [[transcontinental railroad]]. The sixth and final stage is set inside the enemy's hideout. The recurring bosses include a [[sumo wrestler]], a pair of wrestlers resembling the [[tag team]] [[The Road Warriors]], and a trio of claw-wielding masked acrobats. The final boss, Bladedamus, wields two swords and has a fire breath attack.\n\n==Critical reaction==\n{{Video game reviews\n| YSinclair = 90%<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ysrnry.co.uk/articles/shadowwarriors.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2016-07-31 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160215225706/http://www.ysrnry.co.uk/articles/shadowwarriors.htm |archivedate=2016-02-15 }}</ref>\n| CRASH = 74%<ref>{{cite web|url=https://wos.meulie.net/pub/sinclair/magazines/Crash/Issue80/Pages/Crash8000048.jpg |format=JPG |title=Photographic image of game review |website=Wos.meulie.net |accessdate=2016-10-19}}</ref>\n| SUser = 75%<ref>{{cite web|url=https://wos.meulie.net/pub/sinclair/magazines/SinclairUser/Issue103/Pages/SinclairUser10300023.jpg |format=JPG |title=Photographic image of game review |website=Wos.meulie.net |accessdate=2016-10-19}}</ref>\n| CVG = 93%<ref>{{cite web|url=https://wos.meulie.net/pub/sinclair/magazines/Computer-and-Video-Games/Issue103/Pages/CVG10300017.jpg |format=JPG |title=Photographic image of game review |website=Wos.meulie.net |accessdate=2016-10-19}}</ref>\n| rev1 = ''[[Zzap!64]]''\n| rev1Score = 57%<ref>http://www.zzap64.co.uk/cgi-bin/displaypage.pl?issue=065&amp;page=079&amp;thumbstart=0&amp;magazine=zzap&amp;check=1</ref>\n}}\nThe game was well received. ''Your Sinclair'' praised the colorful graphics and interactive backgrounds. ''Crash'' liked the animation, but had grown tired of the genre. ''Sinclair User'' summed it up with \"There isn't really a speck of originality about Shadow Warriors. Nonetheless, it will be a stiff challenge.\" ''C+VG'' highlighted the music and sound effects.\n\n==Version differences==\n===Regional differences===\n''Ninja Ryukenden'', the [[Japan]]ese version, being the later version of the game, has the following differences from the other versions:\n* The ''Ninja Ryukenden'' version has a copyright date of 1989 instead of 1988, as befitting its later release. The Famicom version of ''Ninja Ryukenden'' was already released when the arcade game was distributed in Japan.<ref name=famimaga198901 />\n* The background music for Stage 4 was replaced by another tune that resembles in some parts [[Bach]]'s [[Toccata and Fugue in D Minor]]. And though the other background music tunes are the same as in the U.S. version, there are some minor additions to the tunes in the Japanese version.\n* The enemy characters cause normal damage during the final stage (a three-hit combo takes one square of player's life bar), unlike the U.S. version, where at the last stage, the standard enemies and the mid-bosses just need to hit the player once to take off one or two life squares, and the last boss can kill the player's character with just one attack.\n* A digitized voice shouts the game's title on the \"stage clear\" screen.\n\n===Virtual Console And Hamster Corp. Versions===\nThis game has been ported to the Nintendo Wii as a downloadable Virtual Console Arcade game. However, this contains the same changes found in ''Ninja Gaiden Black''.\n*The boss music in Stages 2 and 5 has been omitted from this version (due to the supposed similarity to [[Black Sabbath|Black Sabbath's]] \"[[Iron Man (song)|Iron Man]]\"); in turn, the regular background music keeps playing even after the bosses appear (which would normally prompt the quick music switch).\n*The use of the [[Star of David]] in the game's imagery (such as the rug at the end of Stage 4) was edited out.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Ninja Gaiden|''Ninja Gaiden'' series]]\n*''[[Rygar]]'', another Tecmo game referenced in background graffiti.\n\n==Notes==\n{{note