{"title_page": "Metal Black (video game)", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{Infobox video game\n|title         = Metal Black\n|image         = Metal Black arcade flyer.jpg\n|caption       = European Arcade flyer\n|developer     = [[Taito]]{{efn|Ported to Sega Saturn by Ving Co., Ltd.}}\n|publisher     = [[Taito]]<br />Ving Co., Ltd. <small>(Saturn)</small>\n|producer      = Takamasa Hori\n|designer      = Takatsuna Senba\n|programmer    = Naoya Kuroki<br />Takashi Seguchi\n|artist        = Ohno Wepokichi\n|composer      = Yasuhisa Watanabe\n|platforms     ={{collapsible list|title=[[Arcade game|Arcade]]|titlestyle=font-weight:normal;font-size:inherit;background:transparent;text-align:left|[[Microsoft Windows]]<br />[[PlayStation 2]]<br />[[Sega Saturn]]<br />[[Xbox]]}}\n|released      ={{collapsible list|title=[[1991 in video gaming|1991]]|titlestyle=font-weight:normal;font-size:inherit;background:transparent;text-align:left|'''Arcade'''{{vgrelease|JP|30 September 1991<ref name=\"ah\">{{cite web|url=https://www.arcade-history.com/?n=metal-black&page=detail&id=1610|title=Metal Black|website=arcade-history.com|accessdate=2018-10-02|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181002141632/https://www.arcade-history.com/?n=metal-black&page=detail&id=1610|archive-date=October 2, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>|EU|1991}} '''Saturn'''<br />''Original release''{{vgrelease|JP|24 May [[1996 in video gaming|1996]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tk-nz.game.coocan.jp/gamedatabase/software/DB_SGC3_SS1996.html|title=SEGA SATURN Soft > 1996|publisher=GAME Data Room|accessdate=2018-10-02|language=ja|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180923085535/http://tk-nz.game.coocan.jp/gamedatabase/software/DB_SGC3_SS1996.html|archive-date=September 23, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>}} ''Re-release''{{vgrelease|JP|27 July [[1998 in video gaming|1998]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tk-nz.game.coocan.jp/gamedatabase/software/DB_SGC3_SS1998.html|title=SEGA SATURN Soft > 1998|publisher=GAME Data Room|accessdate=2019-05-25|language=ja}}</ref>}} '''Taito Legends 2'''{{vgrelease|EU|[[2006 in video gaming|2006]]|NA|[[2007 in video gaming|2007]]}}}}\n|genre         = [[Shoot 'em up#Scrolling shooters|Scrolling shooter]]\n|modes         = {{flatlist|\n*[[Single-player video game|Single-player]]\n*[[Cooperative gameplay|Co-op]]}}\n|cabinet       = [[Arcade cabinet#Upright cabinets|Upright]]\n|arcade system = [[Arcade system board#Taito|Taito F1 System]]<ref name=\"s16\">{{cite web|url=http://www.system16.com/hardware.php?id=662&page=1#1670|title=Taito F1 System Hardware (Taito)|website=system16.com|accessdate=2019-06-02|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170921014356/http://system16.com/hardware.php?id=662&page=1#1670|archive-date=September 21, 2017|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n|cpu           = [[Motorola 68000|68000]] (@ 12 [[MHz]])<ref name=\"s16\"/>\n|sound         = Sound CPU:<br />[[Zilog Z80|Z80]] (@ 4 MHz),<br />[[Sound chip]]s:<ref name=\"s16\"/><br />[[YM2610]]\n|display       = [[Raster graphics|Raster]], 320 \u00d7 224 pixels (Horizontal)\n}}\n\n{{nihongo foot|'''''Metal Black'''''|\u30e1\u30bf\u30eb\u30d6\u30e9\u30c3\u30af|''Metaru Burakku''||lead=yes|group=lower-alpha}} is a [[shoot 'em up]] [[Arcade game|arcade]] [[video game]] developed and originally released by [[Taito]] in Japan on September [[1991 in video gaming|1991]].<ref name=\"ah\"/> The game was produced under the working title \"Project [[Gun Frontier (video game)|Gun Frontier]] 2\"; it was developed by the team behind ''Gun Frontier'', including the game designer Takatsuna Senba, although its actual connection to ''Gun Frontier'' is very loose.\n\nPlayers control the Black Fly on their mission to defeat the forces of Nemesis in hopes of saving the human race. Players collect many small power-ups to build their weapon's power; they can then unleash a large beam attack that drains said power level back to zero. Bosses can also collect these power-ups and use similar beam attacks. When a player's beam collides with a that of a boss, it culminates in a spectacular reaction, the more powerful attack pushing the weaker one aside.\n\n== Gameplay ==\n[[File:ARC Metal Black.png|thumb|left|Gameplay screenshot featuring Apartheid, the first boss of the game, showcasing an example of 'beam-dueling' in ''Metal Black''. The blue beam on the left is the player's beam.]]\nThe gameplay of Metal Black is unique in that there are no alternate weapons or bombs: the player's only weapon power-ups are the innumerable Newalone molecules scattered by Nemesis. Collecting Newalone increases the player's beam level, which serves as the player's only defense. The more Newalone the player picks up, the stronger their standard beam becomes.\n\nWhen reaching mid-level or maximum level on the ship's Beam Level gauge, the player can then unleash a large beam capable of destroying various enemies as well as causing a lightning effect that briefly shocks the screen and consequentially destroys enemies behind and around the Black Fly.<ref name=\"shmups\">{{cite web|url=http://shmups.classicgaming.gamespy.com/reviews/metalblack/index.html/|title=METAL BLACK|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071016071508/http://shmups.classicgaming.gamespy.com/reviews/metalblack/index.html|archivedate=2007-10-16}}</ref>\n\nHowever, certain enemies also have beam gauges of their own, most notably the end-level bosses who in turn collect as much Newalone as they can to unleash their own beam weapon. When the player and the boss' beam weapons fire simultaneously, one beam overpowers the other depending on how high each gauge is, initiating a 'Beam Duel.' The player must mash the beam button rapidly in order to keep the opposing beam blast at bay, which accumulates into a large ball of destructive matter. The blast changes in color depending on which wielder's beam is stronger.<ref name=\"shmups\"/>\n\nThe game has six levels. After the first and fourth, a Bonus Stage occurs to indicate the player's advancement into space (the first bonus stage occurs when the player leaves Earth's atmosphere and the second occurs as they enter a [[worm hole]] as a shortcut to Jupiter). Each Bonus stage has the player encircle a group of crustacean-shaped enemies. The player has to lock on to the moving targets in order to launch cluster missiles at them for extra points. Each bonus stage is timed so as to challenge the player in seeking and destroying before the timer runs out.\n\n== Story ==\nThe year is 2042: A [[companion star]] of the planet [[Jupiter]] appears a few [[Astronomical unit]]s away from the planet and propels the asteroids along Jupiter's orbit towards the Earth, creating a wave of meteorites. As the Earthlings struggle to survive, extraterrestrial [[cybernetic]] invaders from beyond the distant star use the meteorites as cover to invade Earth with little resistance, intending to plunder Earth for inorganic materials needed to sustain their forms. Both the aliens and the star they came from are quickly named 'Nemesis.'\n\nWhat resistance the aliens face from Earth's combined international defense forces is quickly obliterated by the aliens' powerful beam weapons. Earth's scientists study the molecules that power the alien weaponry, which have started to litter the Earth, and the molecule is given the name 'Newalone.' With Newalone in their hands, scientists quickly begin Project Metal Black, focused on developing at least twenty-thousand human spacecraft capable of wielding the same beam-weaponry as the aliens. The spacecraft is known as the CF-345 Black Fly, named for its method of Newalone energy use.\n\nHowever, ten years after the invasion, Earth's remaining diplomats pass a treaty with the Nemesis forces outlining a peaceful surrender, which promises to keep all of Earth's remaining forces from attacking: This applies to Project Metal Black, preventing the Black Fly spacecraft's use. With the planet's population thinning and natural resources depleting, a rogue pilot commandeers one of the Black Fly craft in violation of the treaty, intending to strike back against Nemesis and save what remains of humanity.\n\nThe events within the game itself unfold over six stages as the Black Fly pilot travels to Jupiter, confronting powerful Nemesis ships along the way. In the final two stages, the pilot breaches Nemesis itself, earning a crucial chance to defeat the invading forces once and for all. From this point, there are two possible endings: If the player gets a Game Over on the final stage, the pilot's death incites a military [[coup d'\u00e9tat]] of the global government, and 20,000 Black Fly craft are dispatched to Nemesis's apparent origin point. Otherwise, the pilot confronts the leader of Nemesis in a rapidly-shifting dimension, the battle apparently culminating with the Earth being split in two; it is left unclear as to whether the Earth's destruction and the events of the game as a whole ever actually occurred.\n\n== Development and release ==\n''Metal Black'' was developed under the working title \"Project [[Gun Frontier (video game)|Gun Frontier]] 2\", and shares many of the staff behind ''[[Gun Frontier (video game)|Gun Frontier]]'', including its game designer Takatsuna Senba. However, its actual connection to ''Gun Frontier'' is faint at best. The game has ties to the other Taito shoot-em-up ''[[Darius (series)|Darius]]'' series, as it features a select few marine-themed enemies from it (e.g. [[Ocean sunfish|sunfish]]-shaped ships, Feeder's similarity to a giant [[rattail]], [[diatom]]like enemies in the fourth stage, the giant [[Opabinia]] that supports and powers Daio-to-Gishiin at the end of the third stage, and the aircraft carrier-bearing [[hermit crab]] in the middle of the first stage).\n\n''Metal Black'' was released in arcades in September 1991.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.famitsu.com/cominy/?a=page_h_title&title_id=000000025311|title=\u30e1\u30bf\u30eb\u30d6\u30e9\u30c3\u30af [\u30a2\u30fc\u30b1\u30fc\u30c9] / \u30d5\u30a1\u30df\u901a.com|website=www.famitsu.com|access-date=2018-08-03|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180803194430/https://www.famitsu.com/cominy/?a=page_h_title&title_id=000000025311|archive-date=August 3, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> It was initially ported in 1996 to the [[Sega Saturn]] by VING under the budget line \"Arcade Gears\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.famitsu.com/cominy/?a=page_h_title&title_id=14849|title=\u30e1\u30bf\u30eb\u30d6\u30e9\u30c3\u30af [\u30bb\u30ac\u30b5\u30bf\u30fc\u30f3] / \u30d5\u30a1\u30df\u901a.com|website=www.famitsu.com|access-date=2018-08-03|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180804013839/https://www.famitsu.com/cominy/?a=page_h_title&title_id=14849|archive-date=August 4, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> In 2006, it was included in the compilation ''[[Taito Legends 2]]'' for [[Microsoft Windows|Windows]], [[Xbox (console)|Xbox]], and [[PlayStation 2]].{{Citation needed|date=April 2019}} In 2012, a compilation album containing the soundtrack to the game as well as the soundtracks for ''[[Gun Frontier (video game)|Gun Frontier]]'' and ''[[Dino Rex]]'' was released.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.famitsu.com/news/201212/19026262.html|title=\"\u30b9\u30fc\u30d1\u30fc\u30b9\u30a3\u30fc\u30d7\"\u306e12\u6708\u65b0\u8b5c\u30b2\u30fc\u30e0\u30df\u30e5\u30fc\u30b8\u30c3\u30afCD\uff06\u30a4\u30d9\u30f3\u30c8\u60c5\u5831|date=December 19, 2012|work=Famitsu|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170831133610/https://www.famitsu.com/news/201212/19026262.html|archive-date=August 31, 2017|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n== Reception ==\n{{Video game reviews\n|rev1      = ''[[AllGame]]''\n|rev1Score = (Arcade) {{Rating|2|5}}<ref name=\"AGACmb\">{{cite web|last=Knight|first=Kyle|url=http://www.allgame.com/game.php?id=10514&tab=review|title=Metal Black (Arcade) - Review|website=[[AllGame]]|accessdate=2019-04-10|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141116022402/http://www.allgame.com/game.php?id=10514&tab=review|archivedate=2014-11-16|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|rev2      = ''[[Famitsu]]''\n|rev2Score = (Saturn) 20 / 40<ref name=\"WFTSATmb\">{{cite magazine|url=http://www.famitsu.com/cominy/?m=pc&a=page_h_title&title_id=14849|title=\u30e1\u30bf\u30eb\u30d6\u30e9\u30c3\u30af [\u30bb\u30ac\u30b5\u30bf\u30fc\u30f3] / \u30d5\u30a1\u30df\u901a.com|magazine=[[Famitsu]]|issue=389|publisher=[[ASCII Corporation|ASCII]]|date=May 31, 1996|page=30|access-date=2019-04-10|lang=ja|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130526073834/http://www.famitsu.com/cominy/?m=pc&a=page_h_title&title_id=14849|archive-date=May 26, 2013|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n|rev3      = ''Fun Generation''\n|rev3Score = (Saturn) 4 / 10<ref name=\"FGSATmb\">{{cite magazine|last1=Binzenh\u00f6fer|first1=Andreas|last2=Hellert|first2=Stefan|title=Spiele Tests - Metal Black (Saturn)|magazine=Fun Generation|issue=7|publisher=[[:de:CyPress|CyPress]]|date=August 1996|page=79|lang=de}}</ref>\n|rev4      = ''[[:fr:Joypad (magazine)|Joypad]]''\n|rev4Score = (Saturn) 1 / 5<ref name=\"JSATmb\">{{cite magazine|last=Pr\u00e9zeau|first=Olivier|title=Japon Test - Zapping - Saturn - Metal Black|magazine=[[:fr:Joypad (magazine)|Joypad]]|issue=55|publisher=[[:fr:Yellow Media|Yellow Media]]|date=August 1996|page=72|lang=fr}}</ref>\n|rev5      = ''neXt Level''\n|rev5Score = (Saturn) 65%<ref name=\"XLSATmb\">{{cite magazine|last=Hartwig|first=K.-D.|title=Test - Saturn - Metal Black|magazine=neXt Level|issue=4|publisher=X-plain Verlag GmbH|date=August 1996|page=64|lang=de}}</ref>\n|rev6      = ''[[:ja:\u30b2\u30fc\u30de\u30ac#SEGA SATURN MAGAZINE|Sega Saturn Magazine]] (JP)''\n|rev6Score = (Saturn) 7.33 / 10<ref name=\"SSMjpSATmb\">{{cite magazine|last=|first=|title=Sega Saturn Soft Review - New Release Title Check! - \u30e1\u30bf\u30eb\u30d6\u30e9\u30c3\u30af|magazine=[[:ja:\u30b2\u30fc\u30de\u30ac#SEGA SATURN MAGAZINE|Sega Saturn Magazine]]|issue=23|publisher=[[SB Creative|SoftBank Creative]]|date=June 14, 1996|page=229|lang=ja}}</ref>\n}}\n\n''[[Famitsu]]'' gave the Sega Saturn version a score of 20 out of 40.<ref name=\"WFTSATmb\"/>\n\n=== Legacy ===\nA similar \"beam duel\" combat system was featured in Taito's ''[[G-Darius]]''. The game ''[[Border Down]]'' (made by [[G.rev]], which includes many former Taito employees) also featured such a system, and the game itself references ''Metal Black'' in other ways. The Black Fly appears as a downloadable ship for Taito's ''[[Dariusburst|Dariusburst: Chronicle Saviours]]'' for [[PlayStation 4]], [[PlayStation Vita]], and [[Personal computer|PC]].\n\n{{clear}}\n\n== Notes ==\n{{notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://gamefaqs.gamespot.com/arcade/568260-metal-black ''Metal Black''] at [[GameFAQs]]\n* [https://www.giantbomb.com/metal-black/3030-22403/ ''Metal Black''] at [[Giant Bomb]]\n* [https://www.arcade-museum.com/game_detail.php?game_id=8671 ''Metal Black''] at [[Killer List of Videogames]]\n* [https://www.mobygames.com/game/metal-black ''Metal Black''] at [[MobyGames]]\n\n{{Darius series}}\n{{Portal bar|1990s|Japan|Video games}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Metal Black (video game)}}\n[[Category:1991 video games]]\n[[Category:Arcade games]]\n[[Category:Cooperative video games]]\n[[Category:Horizontally scrolling shooters]]\n[[Category:Post-apocalyptic video games]]\n[[Category:Sega Saturn games]]\n[[Category:Taito games]]\n[[Category:Taito arcade games]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in Japan]]\n[[Category:Video games with alternate endings]]\n[[Category:Video games scored by Yasuhisa Watanabe]]\n[[Category:Video games set in the 2050s]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{Infobox video game\n|title         = Metal Black\n|image         = Metal Black arcade flyer.jpg\n|caption       = European Arcade flyer\n|developer     = [[Taito]]{{efn|Ported to Sega Saturn by Ving Co., Ltd.}}\n|publisher     = [[Taito]]<br />Ving Co., Ltd. <small>(Saturn)</small>\n|producer      = Takamasa Hori\n|designer      = Takatsuna Senba\n|programmer    = Naoya Kuroki<br />Takashi Seguchi\n|artist        = Ohno Wepokichi\n|composer      = Yasuhisa Watanabe\n|platforms     ={{collapsible list|title=[[Arcade game|Arcade]]|titlestyle=font-weight:normal;font-size:inherit;background:transparent;text-align:left|[[Microsoft Windows]]<br />[[PlayStation 2]]<br />[[Sega Saturn]]<br />[[Xbox]]}}\n|released      ={{collapsible list|title=[[1991 in video gaming|1991]]|titlestyle=font-weight:normal;font-size:inherit;background:transparent;text-align:left|'''Arcade'''{{vgrelease|JP|September 1991<ref name=\"ah\">{{cite web|url=https://www.arcade-history.com/?n=metal-black&page=detail&id=1610|title=Metal Black|website=arcade-history.com|accessdate=2018-10-02|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181002141632/https://www.arcade-history.com/?n=metal-black&page=detail&id=1610|archive-date=October 2, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>|EU|1991}} '''Saturn'''<br />''Original release''{{vgrelease|JP|24 May [[1996 in video gaming|1996]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tk-nz.game.coocan.jp/gamedatabase/software/DB_SGC3_SS1996.html|title=SEGA SATURN Soft > 1996|publisher=GAME Data Room|accessdate=2018-10-02|language=ja|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180923085535/http://tk-nz.game.coocan.jp/gamedatabase/software/DB_SGC3_SS1996.html|archive-date=September 23, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>}} ''Re-release''{{vgrelease|JP|27 July [[1998 in video gaming|1998]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tk-nz.game.coocan.jp/gamedatabase/software/DB_SGC3_SS1998.html|title=SEGA SATURN Soft > 1998|publisher=GAME Data Room|accessdate=2019-05-25|language=ja}}</ref>}} '''Taito Legends 2'''{{vgrelease|EU|[[2006 in video gaming|2006]]|NA|[[2007 in video gaming|2007]]}}}}\n|genre         = [[Shoot 'em up#Scrolling shooters|Scrolling shooter]]\n|modes         = {{flatlist|\n*[[Single-player video game|Single-player]]\n*[[Cooperative gameplay|Co-op]]}}\n|cabinet       = [[Arcade cabinet#Upright cabinets|Upright]]\n|arcade system = [[Arcade system board#Taito|Taito F1 System]]<ref name=\"s16\">{{cite web|url=http://www.system16.com/hardware.php?id=662&page=1#1670|title=Taito F1 System Hardware (Taito)|website=system16.com|accessdate=2019-06-02|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170921014356/http://system16.com/hardware.php?id=662&page=1#1670|archive-date=September 21, 2017|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n|cpu           = [[Motorola 68000|68000]] (@ 12 [[MHz]])<ref name=\"s16\"/>\n|sound         = Sound CPU:<br />[[Zilog Z80|Z80]] (@ 4 MHz),<br />[[Sound chip]]s:<ref name=\"s16\"/><br />[[YM2610]]\n|display       = [[Raster graphics|Raster]], 320 \u00d7 224 pixels (Horizontal)\n}}\n\n{{nihongo foot|'''''Metal Black'''''|\u30e1\u30bf\u30eb\u30d6\u30e9\u30c3\u30af|''Metaru Burakku''||lead=yes|group=lower-alpha}} is a [[shoot 'em up]] [[Arcade game|arcade]] [[video game]] developed and originally released by [[Taito]] in Japan on September [[1991 in video gaming|1991]].<ref name=\"ah\"/> The game was produced under the working title \"Project [[Gun Frontier (video game)|Gun Frontier]] 2\"; it was developed by the team behind ''Gun Frontier'', including the game designer Takatsuna Senba, although its actual connection to ''Gun Frontier'' is very loose.\n\nPlayers control the Black Fly on their mission to defeat the forces of Nemesis in hopes of saving the human race. Players collect many small power-ups to build their weapon's power; they can then unleash a large beam attack that drains said power level back to zero. Bosses can also collect these power-ups and use similar beam attacks. When a player's beam collides with a that of a boss, it culminates in a spectacular reaction, the more powerful attack pushing the weaker one aside.\n\n== Gameplay ==\n[[File:ARC Metal Black.png|thumb|left|Gameplay screenshot featuring Apartheid, the first boss of the game, showcasing an example of 'beam-dueling' in ''Metal Black''. The blue beam on the left is the player's beam.]]\nThe gameplay of Metal Black is unique in that there are no alternate weapons or bombs: the player's only weapon power-ups are the innumerable Newalone molecules scattered by Nemesis. Collecting Newalone increases the player's beam level, which serves as the player's only defense. The more Newalone the player picks up, the stronger their standard beam becomes.\n\nWhen reaching mid-level or maximum level on the ship's Beam Level gauge, the player can then unleash a large beam capable of destroying various enemies as well as causing a lightning effect that briefly shocks the screen and consequentially destroys enemies behind and around the Black Fly.<ref name=\"shmups\">{{cite web|url=http://shmups.classicgaming.gamespy.com/reviews/metalblack/index.html/|title=METAL BLACK|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071016071508/http://shmups.classicgaming.gamespy.com/reviews/metalblack/index.html|archivedate=2007-10-16}}</ref>\n\nHowever, certain enemies also have beam gauges of their own, most notably the end-level bosses who in turn collect as much Newalone as they can to unleash their own beam weapon. When the player and the boss' beam weapons fire simultaneously, one beam overpowers the other depending on how high each gauge is, initiating a 'Beam Duel.' The player must mash the beam button rapidly in order to keep the opposing beam blast at bay, which accumulates into a large ball of destructive matter. The blast changes in color depending on which wielder's beam is stronger.<ref name=\"shmups\"/>\n\nThe game has six levels. After the first and fourth, a Bonus Stage occurs to indicate the player's advancement into space (the first bonus stage occurs when the player leaves Earth's atmosphere and the second occurs as they enter a [[worm hole]] as a shortcut to Jupiter). Each Bonus stage has the player encircle a group of crustacean-shaped enemies. The player has to lock on to the moving targets in order to launch cluster missiles at them for extra points. Each bonus stage is timed so as to challenge the player in seeking and destroying before the timer runs out.\n\n== Story ==\nThe year is 2042: A [[companion star]] of the planet [[Jupiter]] appears a few [[Astronomical unit]]s away from the planet and propels the asteroids along Jupiter's orbit towards the Earth, creating a wave of meteorites. As the Earthlings struggle to survive, extraterrestrial [[cybernetic]] invaders from beyond the distant star use the meteorites as cover to invade Earth with little resistance, intending to plunder Earth for inorganic materials needed to sustain their forms. Both the aliens and the star they came from are quickly named 'Nemesis.'\n\nWhat resistance the aliens face from Earth's combined international defense forces is quickly obliterated by the aliens' powerful beam weapons. Earth's scientists study the molecules that power the alien weaponry, which have started to litter the Earth, and the molecule is given the name 'Newalone.' With Newalone in their hands, scientists quickly begin Project Metal Black, focused on developing at least twenty-thousand human spacecraft capable of wielding the same beam-weaponry as the aliens. The spacecraft is known as the CF-345 Black Fly, named for its method of Newalone energy use.\n\nHowever, ten years after the invasion, Earth's remaining diplomats pass a treaty with the Nemesis forces outlining a peaceful surrender, which promises to keep all of Earth's remaining forces from attacking: This applies to Project Metal Black, preventing the Black Fly spacecraft's use. With the planet's population thinning and natural resources depleting, a rogue pilot commandeers one of the Black Fly craft in violation of the treaty, intending to strike back against Nemesis and save what remains of humanity.\n\nThe events within the game itself unfold over six stages as the Black Fly pilot travels to Jupiter, confronting powerful Nemesis ships along the way. In the final two stages, the pilot breaches Nemesis itself, earning a crucial chance to defeat the invading forces once and for all. From this point, there are two possible endings: If the player gets a Game Over on the final stage, the pilot's death incites a military [[coup d'\u00e9tat]] of the global government, and 20,000 Black Fly craft are dispatched to Nemesis's apparent origin point. Otherwise, the pilot confronts the leader of Nemesis in a rapidly-shifting dimension, the battle apparently culminating with the Earth being split in two; it is left unclear as to whether the Earth's destruction and the events of the game as a whole ever actually occurred.\n\n== Development and release ==\n''Metal Black'' was developed under the working title \"Project [[Gun Frontier (video game)|Gun Frontier]] 2\", and shares many of the staff behind ''[[Gun Frontier (video game)|Gun Frontier]]'', including its game designer Takatsuna Senba. However, its actual connection to ''Gun Frontier'' is faint at best. The game has ties to the other Taito shoot-em-up ''[[Darius (series)|Darius]]'' series, as it features a select few marine-themed enemies from it (e.g. [[Ocean sunfish|sunfish]]-shaped ships, Feeder's similarity to a giant [[rattail]], [[diatom]]like enemies in the fourth stage, the giant [[Opabinia]] that supports and powers Daio-to-Gishiin at the end of the third stage, and the aircraft carrier-bearing [[hermit crab]] in the middle of the first stage).\n\n''Metal Black'' was released in arcades in September 1991.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.famitsu.com/cominy/?a=page_h_title&title_id=000000025311|title=\u30e1\u30bf\u30eb\u30d6\u30e9\u30c3\u30af [\u30a2\u30fc\u30b1\u30fc\u30c9] / \u30d5\u30a1\u30df\u901a.com|website=www.famitsu.com|access-date=2018-08-03|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180803194430/https://www.famitsu.com/cominy/?a=page_h_title&title_id=000000025311|archive-date=August 3, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> It was initially ported in 1996 to the [[Sega Saturn]] by VING under the budget line \"Arcade Gears\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.famitsu.com/cominy/?a=page_h_title&title_id=14849|title=\u30e1\u30bf\u30eb\u30d6\u30e9\u30c3\u30af [\u30bb\u30ac\u30b5\u30bf\u30fc\u30f3] / \u30d5\u30a1\u30df\u901a.com|website=www.famitsu.com|access-date=2018-08-03|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180804013839/https://www.famitsu.com/cominy/?a=page_h_title&title_id=14849|archive-date=August 4, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> In 2006, it was included in the compilation ''[[Taito Legends 2]]'' for [[Microsoft Windows|Windows]], [[Xbox (console)|Xbox]], and [[PlayStation 2]].{{Citation needed|date=April 2019}} In 2012, a compilation album containing the soundtrack to the game as well as the soundtracks for ''[[Gun Frontier (video game)|Gun Frontier]]'' and ''[[Dino Rex]]'' was released.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.famitsu.com/news/201212/19026262.html|title=\"\u30b9\u30fc\u30d1\u30fc\u30b9\u30a3\u30fc\u30d7\"\u306e12\u6708\u65b0\u8b5c\u30b2\u30fc\u30e0\u30df\u30e5\u30fc\u30b8\u30c3\u30afCD\uff06\u30a4\u30d9\u30f3\u30c8\u60c5\u5831|date=December 19, 2012|work=Famitsu|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170831133610/https://www.famitsu.com/news/201212/19026262.html|archive-date=August 31, 2017|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n== Reception ==\n{{Video game reviews\n|rev1      = ''[[AllGame]]''\n|rev1Score = (Arcade) {{Rating|2|5}}<ref name=\"AGACmb\">{{cite web|last=Knight|first=Kyle|url=http://www.allgame.com/game.php?id=10514&tab=review|title=Metal Black (Arcade) - Review|website=[[AllGame]]|accessdate=2019-04-10|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141116022402/http://www.allgame.com/game.php?id=10514&tab=review|archivedate=2014-11-16|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|rev2      = ''[[Famitsu]]''\n|rev2Score = (Saturn) 20 / 40<ref name=\"WFTSATmb\">{{cite magazine|url=http://www.famitsu.com/cominy/?m=pc&a=page_h_title&title_id=14849|title=\u30e1\